Andre wrote:


> I want you and everyone know that the definition of a braiding in your
> notes [...] is wrong.  But the definition given in the nLab [...] is
> correct.
>

Thanks - I fixed the typo.  I don't feel too bad, because the definition in
the nLab had just one hexagon axiom until I put in the second one.

The Breen-Baez-Dolan Stabilisation Hypothesis is a theorem.
>

Great.  How do you prove it?  And which definition of n-category are you
using?  You write:

*If a n-type has the structure of an E(n+2)-space then it has the the
> structure of an E(infty)-space (canonically)*
>
> This is a special case of the Stabilisation Hypothesis of Breen-Baez-Dolan;
>
> *If a n-category has the structure of an E(n+2)-category then it has the
> structure of
> symmetric monoidal category (canonically)*
>
> (Equivalently, *If a monoidal n-category is (n+1)-braided then it has the
> structure of
> symmetric monoidal category (canonically)*)
>
> It is not difficult to verify that these statements are formally
> equivalent.
>
> The Breen-Baez-Dolan Stabilisation Hypothesis is a theorem.
>

It seems I understand everything except the last sentence.

